03739nam a22006135i 9780271031101DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20012000pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710311017 a10.1515/97802710311012doi  a(DE-B1597)583741  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aHQ1190.M378 2000 7aPOL0420202bisacsh04a321.8/6/011 aMatthes, Melissa, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Rape of Lucretia and the Founding of Republics :bReadings in Livy, Machiavelli, and Rousseau /cMelissa Matthes. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2001] 4c©2000  a1 online resource (192 p.) :b1 illustration  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- t1 A Conversation Between Republicanism and Feminism -- t2 Livy and the Repetition of Republican Foundations -- t3 La Mandragola and the Seduction of Lucrezia -- t4 The Seriously Comedic, or Why Machiavelli's Lucrezia Is Not Livy's Virtuous Roman -- t5 The Paradox of Rousseau's Politics and the Return to the Founding -- t6 Nouvelle Héloïse and the Supplement of Sexual Difference -- t7 Concluding Remarks -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe bonds among republican citizens are created, in part, through the stories told and retold as the foundational myths of the republic. In this book, Melissa Matthes takes advantage of the way in which republican theorists in different eras-Livy, Machiavelli, and Rousseau-retell the story of the rape of Lucretia to support their own conceptions of republicanism.The recurring presentation of this story as theater by these different theorists reveals not only the performative elements of republicanism but, as Matthes argues, adds to Hannah Arendt's emphasis on the oral dimensions of speech and hearing the important idea of public space as a visual field. Lucretia's story also helps illuminate the gendering of republicanism, particularly the aspects of violence and subordination that lie at its very origin. By focusing attention on this underlying and deeply gendered quality of republics, Matthes brings republican theory into fruitful dialogue with feminism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Ideologies / Conservatism & Liberalism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311074526940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271031101423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780271031101.jpg  a978-3-11-074526-9  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK